The original Java code uses in.next(), which reads a token, so probably the input is a single word without whitespace. So in C, using scanf %s is safe. So the steps are:

1. Read the string using scanf. 2. Check each character for A and B.
3. Output Yes or No based on the flags. Now, code structure. The main function will handle this. No need for classes or methods like in Java. Sample code outline:

#include <stdio.h>
#include <string.h>

int main() {
    char s[100]; // Assuming a reasonable max length
    scanf("%s", s);
    int hasA = 0, hasB = 0;
    for (int i = 0; s[i] ! = '\0'; i++) {
        if (s[i] == 'A') {
            hasA = 1;
        } else if (s[i] == 'B') {
            hasB = 1;
        }
    } if (hasA && hasB) {
        printf("Yes\n");
    } else {
        printf("No\n");
    }
    return 0;
}

But wait, in the original code, they check if the string contains both 'A' and 'B'. So even if one is present multiple times, as long as both are there once, it's okay. This code should handle that. So the loop will set the flags once any occurrence is found.

